8 An Act relating to electric utilities; creating the
GET Over Congestion (Grid Enhancing Technology Over
9 Congestion) Act; defining terms; requiring utilities
to evaluate the use of certain technologies; stating
10 contents of evaluations; requiring certain
coordination; suggesting utilities make certain
11 consultation with large load users; stating that
certain participation is voluntary; authorizing
12 Corporation Commission to make certain evaluation;
providing that large load customers not be required
13 to fund certain improvements; requiring certain
analysis by utilities; detailing certain
14 requirements; requiring certain contents of filing;
authorizing Commission to approve recovery of certain
15 costs; stating applicability of act; providing for
codification; and providing an effective date.
16
17
18 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
19 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
20 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 860 of Title 17, unless there is
21 created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
22 This act shall be known and may be cited as the "GET Over
23 Congestion (Grid Enhancing Technology Over Congestion) Act".
24
Req. No. 17120 Page 1

1 SECTION 2. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
2 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 861 of Title 17, unless there is
3 created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
4 A. As used in this section:
5 1. "Advanced power flow controllers" means technologies that
6 modulate circuit impedance or other electrical properties to reroute
7 power flows and relieve congestion;
8 2. "Advanced transmission technology" means a technology that
9 increases the capacity, efficiency, or reliability of electric
10 transmission infrastructure, including grid-enhancing technologies
11 (GETs) such as dynamic line rating, advanced power flow controllers,
12 topology optimization, high-performance conductors, and other
13 technologies designed to reduce transmission congestion;
14 3. "Congestion" means a condition in which transmission
15 capacity constraint prevents the delivery of the lowest cost
16 electricity available to serve load at a specific location;
17 4. "Dynamic line rating" means a system that uses real-time or
18 forecasted weather and operating conditions, including wind speed
19 and direction, to determine the transfer capacity of a transmission
20 line;
21 5. "Grid-enhancing technologies" or "GETs" means technologies
22 that increase the usable capacity of existing transmission
23 infrastructure through hardware, software, or operational tools
24
Req. No. 17120 Page 2

1 incl uding dynamic line rating, advanced power flow controllers,
2 topology optimization, and related technologies;
3 6. "High-performance conductors" means a conductor used in an
4 electric transmission system, including carbon-fiber conductors,
5 composite core conductors, and superconductors that meet one or more
6 of the following criteria:
7 a. electrical resistance that is at least ten percent
8 (10%) lower than a comparable aluminum conductor steel
9 reinforced (ACSR) conductor,
10 b. a carrying capacity at least seventy-five percent
11 (75%) greater than a comparable ACSR conductor, or
12 c. a coefficient of thermal expansion at least thirty
13 percent (30%) less than a comparable ACSR conductor;
14 7. "Integrated resource plan" or "IRP" means a utility's
15 planning document filed with the Oklahoma Corporation Commission
16 pursuant to OAC 165:35-37 or successor rules;
17 8. "Large load customer" means new data centers, new
18 cryptocurrency mining operations and new facilities whose primary
19 function is artificial-intelligence computing facilities that
20 contract with an electric supplier to add seventy-five (75)
21 megawatts or greater electric load per facility or in aggregate
22 behind a single point of interconnection to an electric supplier's
23 load. The term does not include residential, commercial,
24
Req. No. 17120 Page 3

1 agri cultural, or industrial ratepayers, or those entities that build
2 generation for behind-the-meter projects;
3 9. "Topology optimization" means software that identifies
4 switching configurations to reroute electricity and alleviate
5 transmission constraints; and
6 10. "Utility" means an investor-owned electric utility subject
7 to the ratemaking and integrated resource planning authority of the
8 Oklahoma Corporation Commission.
9 B. As part of its transmission and resource planning processes,
10 a utility shall evaluate the cost effectiveness and deployment
11 timeline of advanced transmission technologies and grid-enhancing
12 technologies. Such evaluation shall include consideration of
13 whether the technologies would:
14 1. Increase transmission capacity;
15 2. Increase transmission efficiency;
16 3. Reduce transmission system congestion;
17 4. Reduce curtailment of generation resources;
18 5. Increase reliability;
19 6. Reduce the risk of igniting wildfire;
20 7. Increase resiliency; or
21 8. Increase ability of the system to connect new
22 generation resources.
23
24
Req. No. 17120 Page 4

1 Util ities shall coordinate, where practicable, with regional
2 transmission planning processes including those conducted through
3 the Southwest Power Pool.
4 C. A utility may consult with large load customers to identify
5 opportunities for voluntary collaboration, cost-sharing, or
6 customer-funded pilot deployment of GETs. Participation by large
7 load customers shall be voluntary and subject to review by the
8 Corporation Commission. Where investments provide systemwide
9 benefits to customers, the Corporation Commission may determine
10 appropriate cost allocation through the general rate base.
11 Nothing in this subsection shall be construed to require large
12 load users to fund transmission improvements that primarily benefit
13 the broader system.
14 D. As part of an integrated resource plan filing, a utility
15 shall conduct a transmission congestion analysis that includes:
16 1. Identification of the ten most congested locations on the
17 utility’s transmission system;
18 2. An estimation of the frequency of congestion at each
19 location and the cost to ratepayers resulting from congestion and
20 substitution of higher-priced electricity;
21 3. An evaluation of the technical feasibility and estimated
22 cost of installing advanced transmission technologies to address
23 congestion;
24 4. A comparison of:
Req. No. 17120 Page 5

1 a. the cost of congestion and higher priced electricity,
2 and
3 b. the cost of deploying advanced transmission
4 technologies to relieve congestion; and
5 5. A proposed implementation plan, including estimated
6 schedules and costs where deployment of such technologies may be
7 cost effective.
8 E. A utility shall included in its IRP filing:
9 1. The results of the congestion analysis;
10 2. An evaluation of advanced transmission technologies; and
11 3. A summary of existing and planned deployments of such
12 technologies.
13 F. If the Corporation Commission determines that deployment of
14 advanced transmission technologies is cost effective and in the best
15 interest of ratepayers, the Commission shall approve recovery of
16 prudently incurred costs.
17 G. Nothing in this act shall mandate deployment of any specific
18 transmission technology, favor or disfavor any type of generation
19 resource, or restrict or impede development of behind-the-meter
20 generation or energy projects.
21 SECTION 3. This act shall become effective November 1, 2026.
